Alors qu’en 2005, les émeutes s’étaient étalées sur 3 semaines, les chiffres de la nuit montrent qu’après 5 jours de violences, on n’est plus très loin du retour au calme : par rapport au pic de jeudi, le nombre de voitures incendiées a été divisé par 6, les interpellations par 8 et les bâtiments dégradés par 14. On se détend ? Emmanuel Macron promet -- malgré l'accalmie -- le maintien d’une présence policière "massive" sur place
... et annonce vouloir "débuter un travail minutieux pour comprendre en profondeur les raisons qui ont conduit à ces événements"
translated:
In the suburbs, the reflux of #riots is confirmed. While in 2005, the riots had spread over 3 weeks, the night figures show that after 5 days of violence, we are no longer very far from the return to calm: compared to the peak of Thursday, the Number of burned cars was divided by 6, arrests by 8 and buildings degraded by 14. Do we relax? Emmanuel Macron promises - despite the lull - the maintenance of a "massive" police presence on site
... and announces that he wants to "start a careful work to understand in depth the reasons which led to these events"

tweet_text: J'ai décidé de verser la totalité de ma paye de professeur de philosophie suspendu (quelques douze euros hélas) à la cagnotte en soutien à la famille du policier honteusement accusé d'être "un tueur" par certains démagogues qui se prétendent de gauche. Ce lynchage public m'est aussi insupportable que la mort d'un jeune qui n'avait cependant manifestement plus de repères et se croyait tout permis. Que la société tout entière se réveille et assume enfin ses responsabilités  ! Assez du mensonge permanent dans lequel on se berce du matin au soir et du lundi au dimanche ! Assez de la démission des adultes envers la jeunesse ! Assez de la destruction méthodique de toute autorité et de la promotion de gadgets ! Assez du saccage des institutions, à commencer par celui de l'école qui distribue dorénavant et dans l'hypocrisie générale des diplômes qui ne valent rien à des jeunes qu'on laisse dans un état de quasi illettrisme ! Non mais que croyez-vous ? Que des gosses à qui l'on n'apprend rien vont en plus remercier et marcher droit ? Toutes nos lâchetés collectives et quotidiennes produisent la violence, inévitablement et aussi nécessairement que deux et deux font quatre. Ceux qui sont en première ligne pour assurer malgré tout un semblant d'ordre permettant accessoirement aux bavards de continuer à pérorer tranquillement sur les plateaux de télévision, ce sont les policiers, qui n'en peuvent mais ! Ou bien l'on en sort par le haut en remontant jusqu'aux causes premières pour les traiter, ou bien on laisse les choses aller et les violences auxquelles on vient d'assister apparaîtront a posteriori comme les prémices d'un effondrement beaucoup plus destructeur. C'est évident et tout le monde en réalité le sait.
translated: I decided to pay all of my pay as professor of suspended philosophy (a few twelve euros alas) to the prize pool in support of the family of the policeman ashamed of being "a killer" by certain demagogues who claim to be on the left. This public lynching is as unbearable to me as the death of a young person who had obviously no more bearings and believed himself to be allowed. May the whole company wakes up and finally assume its responsibilities! Enough of the permanent lie in which we rock from morning to evening and from Monday to Sunday! Enough of the resignation of adults to youth! Enough of the methodical destruction of any authority and the promotion of gadgets! Enough of the ransacking of institutions, starting with that of the school which now distributes and in the general hypocrisy of diplomas which are worth nothing to young people who are left in a state of almost illiteracy! No, but what do you think? That kids to whom we learn nothing will thank and walk straight? All our collective and daily cowards produce violence, inevitably and as necessarily as two and two are four. Those who are on the front line to ensure a semblance of an order, accessory to the talkatives to continue quietly on the television sets, are the police officers, who can but! Or else we get out from the top going up to the primary causes to treat them, or else we let things go and the violence to which we have just assisted will appear a posteriori as the beginnings of a much more destructive collapse . It is obvious and everyone in reality knows.

#Russian senator fears for the safety of French nuclear arsenal   
Andrey #Klishas’ remark comes amid #Riots in #France, echoing those made by Western commentators over the Wagner coup attempt last week
twitter.com/leakteleg2024/st…
The ongoing violence on the streets of French cities gives grounds for concern over the safety of the country’s nuclear arsenal, Russian senator Andrey Klishas has suggested. Last week some Western commentators voiced similar worries over the security Russia’s own weapons amid a failed coup attempt by PMC Wagner.

In a series of posts published on his Telegram channel on Saturday, Klishas argued that calls should be made for the “French police to exercise restraint.”

“EU leaders [should] discuss the stability of the political regime in France and check whether the nuclear arsenal is safe,” the politician wrote.

tweet_text:
Ces derniers jours, nous avons tous vu passer des images difficiles sur les réseaux sociaux.

Mais ces réseaux sont aussi des vecteurs de bonnes nouvelles et de messages bienveillants. En voici un !
                 
À vous qui venez d’avoir votre bac : vous pouvez être fiers.

Fiers, vos parents et vos enseignants le sont eux aussi. Votre réussite au baccalauréat, c'est aussi la leur et je veux les saluer, les remercier.

Fiers, nous le sommes toutes et tous, en tant que Nation. Vous nous rendez fiers d'autant plus que vous êtes l’avenir de notre pays, un avenir prometteur, un avenir que vous incarnez déjà avec des valeurs d’écologie, d’égalité et de progrès.

Vous êtes notre raison d'agir et vous n'hésitez d’ailleurs pas à nous le rappeler lorsque nous n'allons pas assez vite et fort. Je vous l'assure : vous restez au centre de toutes mes décisions.

Félicitations pour votre bac.

Bel été à toutes et à tous.
translated:
In recent days, we have all seen difficult images passing on social networks.

But these networks are also vectors of good news and benevolent messages. Here is one!
                 
You have just had your baccalaureate: you can be proud.

Proud, your parents and teachers are too. Your success in the baccalaureate is also theirs and I want to greet them, thank them.

Proud, we are all, as a nation. You make us proud especially since you are the future of our country, a promising future, a future that you already embody with values ​​of ecology, equality and progress.

You are our reason to act and you do not hesitate to remind us when we are not going quickly and strong enough. I assure you: you stay at the center of all my decisions.

Congratulations on your bac.

HAIM MUST TO ALL.

tweet_text:
As #global citizens, it is essential for us to address the critical situation in #France following the tragic death of young #Nahel (God rest his soul in eternal peace). The ongoing #protests and #riots in response to this incident highlight the urgency for justice, accountability, and meaningful reforms. We must advocate for transparency, thorough investigations, and systemic changes that promote social cohesion, equality, and improved relations between communities and law enforcement. It is crucial to support efforts that strive towards a fairer and more just society.

When president #Macron chooses to attend a concert during such a crisis, it is seen as disrespectful and a lack of empathy for the family of young #Nahel (God rest his soul in eternal peace). It can also be seen as a failure to prioritize the needs and concerns of the people. This can lead to public dissatisfaction and criticism, as people may feel that their leader is disconnected from the realities and challenges they are facing.

It is important for #PresidentMacron and his government to strike a balance between their personal activities and their responsibilities during times of crisis. They need to be visible, empathetic, engage with the public, and work towards resolving the issues at hand.

We must acknowledge that certain communities in #France face economic disparities and social challenges, including the existence of ghettos and the terrible conditions in which many people live. These disparities can hinder the integration process and perpetuate social divisions. It is the responsibility of the government to address these challenges and create equal opportunities for all citizens, while actively working to eliminate ghettos and improve housing conditions.

Efforts should be focused on breaking the cycle of poverty, ensuring access to quality education, creating job opportunities, and improving living conditions in marginalized areas. By addressing these socio-economic inequalities, the government can foster greater social cohesion and create an environment where every individual has a fair chance to succeed.

When such a tragic and distressing incident occurs, which leads to widespread and nationwide riots and protests, along with accusations of racism and inequality, it is vital for the #FrenchGovernment to respond comprehensively. This includes conducting thorough investigations, ensuring accountability, and implementing systemic reforms to promote social and economic justice.

Open and transparent communication from the government is crucial in addressing concerns, building trust, and demonstrating a genuine commitment to justice and fairness.

President #Macron and his government must actively engage with communities, seeking their input and participation in decision-making processes that directly affect their lives.

Leadership during times of crisis demands empathy, understanding, and a steadfast commitment to inclusivity and socio-economic progress.

As global citizens, we must advocate for these values, supporting efforts to create a society where every individual, regardless of their background, has an equal opportunity to thrive and contribute.

PROPOSITIONS.

Les Français n'ont pas à payer pour réparer les dégâts des émeutiers.

Chaque année, nous payons 10 milliards d'euros dans la politique de la ville pour financer les banlieues. Un sacrifice financier immense, pour que les banlieues détruisent ce que nous construisons.

Ceux qui cassent doivent désormais être ceux qui payent.

Je propose :

1- Des sanctions financières sévères et dissuasives contre les émeutiers : l'argent des réparations doit venir de leurs poches et pas des nôtres.

2- De sanctionner les familles si les délinquants sont mineurs : ces familles ne doivent plus percevoir d'aides sociales.

3- Des travaux d'intérêt général pour les casseurs : ils cassent, ils reconstruisent eux-mêmes. Cela contribuera à leur éducation s'ils sont français. S'ils sont étrangers, leur place est dans leur pays d'origine.

Les Français ne doivent plus se lever le matin pour ceux qui vivent de leur générosité. Cela s'appelle la justice sociale.
translated:
Proposals.

The French do not have to pay to repair the damage of the rioters.

Each year, we pay 10 billion euros in city policy to finance the suburbs. An immense financial sacrifice, so that the suburbs destroy what we build.

Those who break must now be those who pay.

I propose :

1- Severe and dissuasive financial sanctions against rioters: money from repairs must come from their pockets and not from ours.

2- To punish families if offenders are minor: these families should no longer receive social assistance.

3- Work of general interest for the thugs: they break, they rebuild themselves. This will contribute to their education if they are French. If they are foreigners, their place is in their country of origin.

The French must no longer get up in the morning for those who live in their generosity. This is called social justice.

tweet_text:
#emeutes #FranceRiots
Troupeau qui va, revient, juge, absout, délibère,
Détruit, prêt à Marat comme prêt à Tibère,
Foule triste, joyeuse, habits dorés, bras nus,
Pêle-mêle, et poussée aux gouffres inconnus.
Ils sont les passants froids, sans but, sans nœud, sans âge ;
Le bas du genre humain qui s’écroule en nuage ;
Ceux qu’on ne connaît pas, ceux qu’on ne compte pas,
Ceux qui perdent les mots, les volontés, les pas.
L’ombre obscure autour d’eux se prolonge et recule ;
Ils n’ont du plein midi qu’un lointain crépuscule,
Car, jetant au hasard les cris, les voix, le bruit,
Ils errent près du bord sinistre de la nuit.
translated:
#emeuts #FranceRoots
Herd that goes, returns, judge, absolved, deliberate,
Destroyed, ready for Marat as ready for Tiberius,
Sad, joyful crowd, golden clothes, bare arms,
Peel, and pushed to unknown chasms.
They are the cold passers -by, aimless, without knot, ageless;
The bottom of the human race that collapses in clouds;
Those we don't know, those we don't count,
Those who lose words, wills, steps.
The dark shadow around them extends and retreats;
They only have full lunch a distant twilight,
Because, throwing at random the cries, the voices, the noise,
They wander near the loss edge of the night.

tweet_text:
🧠Decentralization: The Path to Ensuring Freedom of Expression on Social Media

In the current world, there are four things that no one can change: the family you are born into, the nationality you have, your ethnicity, and lastly, censorship on social media.

The Turkish elections have demonstrated that despite Elon's good intentions to make Twitter the digital agora of this era, achieving it in a centralized manner is impossible. Governments, large institutions, and media outlets will do everything possible to pressurize Twitter into censoring comments they dislike, since they have Elon to target. In order for Twitter to reach everyone, it will have to conform to the rules of each country. If a country has censorship rules, like Turkey, Twitter will have to censor content.

I don't understand why Elon is attempting something incredibly mega-bureaucratic, fighting against governments, media outlets, and others to make X the centralized source of truth. A decentralized social network that operates similar to Bitcoin would be a much less bureaucratic option and easier to scale to all countries. Additionally, in this way, individuals in positions of power would not have the means to target a specific person since we are all replaceable within a decentralized system. We are all equally important to a certain degree. In contrast, if something happens to Elon Musk and he is no longer the owner of X, what would happen to the platform? Would it maintain these principles of freedom or return to censorship? Even @jack, the creator of Twitter, thinks the same way.

Utilizing blockchain technology for message validation and transmission is the correct option in my opinion. By paying a small fee, you could express yourself freely and securely forever. Not only that, but the platform could automatically monetize itself, making likes, retweets, and follows a way to reward content creators. The simple act of paying to post tweets would practically eliminate 99% of bots, and users would think twice before tweeting or posting.

I don't believe it will be easy, but I do believe that this is the path to follow. If we want to ensure freedom of expression forever, we cannot rely solely on one person, in this case, Decentralization: The Path to Ensuring Freedom of Expression on Social Media. Instead, we should come together, just as Bitcoin functions, to create the true digital agora of the future.

Elon's work with X is highly appreciated, and it is evident that he is trying everything to make X the source of truth and freedom of expression. However, I believe that for this breakthrough to happen, it needs to be decentralized.

Thank you for reading,
Felix.

🌹🌹🌹

C𐤀W̊

Es sind Verharmlosungen, die sozialpädagogisch Verständnis für eine mörderische Hemmungslosigkeit wecken sollen, die auch in Deutschland bekannt ist: Bei den #Silvesterausschreitungen wurden Krankenwagen angegriffen. Und wir schrecken auch nicht davor zurück, eure Repräsentanten umzubringen.“ Die Faz schreibt:

„Dem 39 Jahre alten Bürgermeister Vincent Jeanbrun steht der Schrecken ins Gesicht geschrieben. Als er während einer neuen unruhigen Nacht im Rathaus von L’Haÿ-les-Roses wachte, haben Unbekannte um 1.30 Uhr am Sonntag mit einem schweren Fahrzeug das Portal seines Wohnhauses durchbrochen. Sie warfen einen Brandsatz. Ein zweiter Brandsatz zündete nicht und wurde im Vorgarten gefunden. Im Haus schliefen die Ehefrau des Bürgermeisters und seine beiden Kinder im Alter von fünf und sieben Jahren. Jeanbruns Frau wurde von dem Krach und Brandgeruch aus dem Schlaf gerissen. Sie konnte sich mit den Kindern in letzter Minute vor den Flammen in den Garten retten. Sie verletzte sich bei der nächtlichen Flucht vor den Gewalttätern und muss wegen eines Schienbeinbruchs im Krankenhaus behandelt werden. Auch eines seiner Kinder wurde verletzt. Beide Kinder stehen unter Schock. „Eine neue Stufe des Schreckens und der Schändlichkeit ist erreicht“, reagierte Jeanbrun. (...)

Am Vorabend war die Bürgermeisterin von Pontoise, Stéphanie von Euw, bei einer nächtlichen Inspektionstour in ihrer Gemeinde von jugendlichen Randalierern in ihrem Auto festgesetzt worden. Auf ihr Fahrzeug sei zunächst mit Feuerwerkskörpern und anderen Wurfgeschossen geworfen worden. Dann seien Jugendliche auf das Dach und die Motorhaube gesprungen, hätten gegen die Scheiben getrommelt und sie bedroht. Ihre Windschutzscheibe sei zerbrochen und sie habe in letzter Minute den Rückwärtsgang einlegen und fliehen können.“

France riots:

           A thread🧵

By now you would have figured out that what is happening in France will also happen here. This is unavoidable as the underlying causes of their problems are also present here as well. An unwarranted fanaticism for multiculturalism and tolerance has led to the assimilation rate of migrants becoming basically zero. Meaning that there is no loyalty from the migrants to their new country. This lack of loyalty means that the relationship between the host nation and the migrants can only go downhill. What seemingly set off the race riots has now spiraled into a civil war between the unassimilated migrants who don’t see themselves as French, and the French people. This comes as no surprise to myself and others likeminded, as we all saw through the thin veil of multiculturalism; clearly seeing multiculturalism as synonymous with multinationalism. And an autonomous nation with widespread ethnic and religious multinationalism will not last long before it falls into civil war and balkanization. Which leads us too now.

France has a population of 68 million, roughly three times the population of Australia, yet their population of immigrants is around 9.5 million, or 14% of the population. Comparatively in Australia, our immigrant population is rising drastically with it being estimated that over 300,000 immigrants and refugees are to be brought to Australia this year alone. This coupled with a policy of multiculturalism and diversity means that soon there will be millions upon millions of foreigners in Australia who identify as being of there previous culture and previous religion. This is the problem that France is facing, but they are further down the path of chaos than we are. We are currently watching a car crash in slow motion.

“The voice” is the perfect example of this brain-dead ideology of multiculturalism turning into blatant multinationalism. It is exactly what Yuri Bezmenov warned the West about when he explained in his 1985 interview how demoralization and destruction of otherwise healthy and powerful nations will play out. “the voice” is the first obvious step into this chaos, as the so called "indigenous" population will begin seeing themselves as a separate nation, to which its enemy is the “colonial white Australia”, a derogatory, racist, and fabricated view of our current unified, rich and powerful federation which we are all equal citizens of. We have been unified for over 100 years, yet now that unity is being torn apart by vested interests.

The US, Britain, Germany, Netherlands, Belgium, New Zealand, and Canada will also be subject to the same fate as France. And although my reader base is largely Australian, I realize that many of you are from these great nations. · An unrealistic and manufactured influx of migrants from violent nations. (Of which most are single, fighting age males)
· Governments which actively accelerate the above problems.
· A large native population of European descendants which are drugged by bread and circus.

And so, there are three parties at work here: The people, The migrants, and the government.

All of them are separate and independent of each other. To say that any major western nation today is run by its native population is a lie. They are either run by foreigners, dual citizens, or people who work for unknown foreign parties. No sane government for and by the people would allow for its nation’s destruction. If Macron was even remotely working in his people’s best interests, he would be directing the army to engage the threat. But he barely even sends local police to deal with the problem. And when they do get sent in, it does nothing but stir up the hive. This would be obvious to the French government. But the French government is obviously no longer French…

(Thread continues…)

Le récit du procureur de la République de Nanterre est glaçant. Un gamin mineur, n'ayant pas de permis, roule à vive allure en agglomération à bord d'un bolide depuis 7h50 du matin. Il emprunte la voie de bus, grille un feu rouge, manque de renverser un piéton, puis un cycliste, est pris en chasse par deux motards, est sommé de s'arrêter à deux reprises, refuse d'obtempérer, est finalement obligé de s'arrêter à cause de la circulation, est arrêté par les motards vers 08h20. Le motard lui pointe son arme dessus et le menace en lui disant qu'il va tirer s'il redémarre. Et le gamin redémarre la voiture.
La suite, on la connaît. Un drame regrettable. Le policier tire. Il aurait dû ne pas tirer.
Mais le gamin, aurait-il dû redémarrer? 
Et pourquoi le fait-il? Parce qu'il n'y a plus de respect de l'autorité. Parce qu'il est en roue libre et il est conscient du laxisme de la justice. Il sait qu'il ne risque rien s'il blesse ou tue un policier ou un autre usager de la route à bord de son bolide. C'est la vérité. Elle déplaît, elle fait mal. Mais, c'est la réalité!
#Nanterre
translated:
The account of the Nanterre Public Prosecutor is chilling. A minor kid, having no license, rolls at high speed in agglomeration aboard a racing car since 7:50 am. He takes the bus lane, grid a red light, fails to overturn a pedestrian, then a cyclist, is hunting by two bikers, is ordered to stop twice, refuses to comply, is ultimately forced to 'Stopping because of traffic is arrested by bikers around 8:20 am. We at the ADC deeply mourn the loss of Nahel, French Algerian teenager recently murdered by French police.  This serves as a painful reminder that the scourges of anti-Arabness, Anti-Amazigh and Islamophobia aren't confined to any one nation's borders. 

We stand with the respective communities around the globe in calling for a stop to such injustices perpetrated by the French government. We firmly condemn the continued discrimination faced by Arabs, Amazigh and Muslims in France, which perpetuates harmful stereotypes, fuels hatred, and threatens the safety of our community members worldwide.

We, as Arab Americans, understand the shared struggle and empathize deeply with the victims of such bias and bigotry. We reaffirm our commitment to promoting understanding, inclusivity, and respect across ethnic and religious lines.

The French government has for far too long masqueraded their vile violence, hatred and bigotry of Arabs, Africans, Amazigh, Muslims and communities of color as “freedom.” They must be held accountable by the global community for their long history of abuses against our collective communities. 

We call for justice for Nahel, and for all victims of racial and religious hatred and violence. #JusticeForNahel

Ces derniers jours, nous avons tous vu passer des images difficiles sur les réseaux sociaux.

Mais ces réseaux sont aussi des vecteurs de bonnes nouvelles et de messages bienveillants. En voici un !
                 
À vous qui venez d’avoir votre bac : vous pouvez être fiers.

Fiers, vos parents et vos enseignants le sont eux aussi. Votre réussite au baccalauréat, c'est aussi la leur et je veux les saluer, les remercier.

Fiers, nous le sommes toutes et tous, en tant que Nation. Vous nous rendez fiers d'autant plus que vous êtes l’avenir de notre pays, un avenir prometteur, un avenir que vous incarnez déjà avec des valeurs d’écologie, d’égalité et de progrès.

Vous êtes notre raison d'agir et vous n'hésitez d’ailleurs pas à nous le rappeler lorsque nous n'allons pas assez vite et fort. Je vous l'assure : vous restez au centre de toutes mes décisions.

Félicitations pour votre bac.

Bel été à toutes et à tous.
translated:
In recent days, we have all seen difficult images passing on social networks.

But these networks are also vectors of good news and benevolent messages. Here is one!
                 
You have just had your baccalaureate: you can be proud.

Proud, your parents and teachers are too. Your success in the baccalaureate is also theirs and I want to greet them, thank them.

Proud, we are all, as a nation. You make us proud especially since you are the future of our country, a promising future, a future that you already embody with values ​​of ecology, equality and progress.

You are our reason to act and you do not hesitate to remind us when we are not going quickly and strong enough. I assure you: you stay at the center of all my decisions.

Congratulations on your bac.

HAIM MUST TO ALL.
